Well it would do 200 DPS if chain casting IC.<br>
<br>
As well this is not only about DPS, it is about blurring class lines... - with a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>pet</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
You have a pretty nice arguement there, with the rogue pet and the warrior pet.<br>
Now you could ask for a bard pet, a cleric pet... what about a druid pet?<br>
<br>
The point i am trying to make is... our classes are already too similiar, and if you are talking about mage dps, many of you forget that that includes PET dps AND Mage nuke DPS.<br>
<br>
The rogue pet backstabs. But as i said before it does not come with a ragebringer. It does not open doors, it does not use poison, it hast not the AA escape abbility etc.<br>
The wizard fire pet on test is using a lot of 'class defining' abbilities.<br>
It uses our fast casting draughts, it uses one of our big bangs (IC) and it uses lures, it uses our high level AE snare.<br>
It uses <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>EVERY</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> single abbility that makes us wizards different from Mages, save Xlocates and GGs.<br>
And that is a tad too much.<br>
<br>
Mage and Wizard are too similiar to each other already (especially with PoP and the redundant Evacs, Gates, etc) there is no need to blurr the class lines even more with a pet and invade now as well our burst DPS niche and our abbility to do big damage with cold based 1k+ nukes. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=natanmagus>Natan Magus</A> at: 5/22/03 11:23:35 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=finsmacgalis>Fins Macgalis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/22/03 12:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: thought you should hear it from a mage first</span><hr size=1> The only problem I find with the fire pet using such big nukes is the fact that pets *DO* pull agro.  The rule only applies for melee range, but we've all seen mobs actually follow pets when a mage or beastlord hit the /pet back off button.  The biggest fear I would see is a fire pet starting the fight with Ice Comet and immedietly drawing agro.  While it's just a pet that doesn't exactly need a rez or anything, it is a nuisance for the group to repeatingly have to deal with this.  This is just speculation though.  I haven't actually seen the new fire pet on test.  Heck, this may not already be a problem.<br>
<br>
There is one thing definite though - <br>
<br>
1)  Wizards don't want the pet casting Ice Comet.<br>
2)  Mages just want the pet to be useful.<br>
<br>
I agree with Jaytee 100% that if the pet does not do comparable damage to the other pets, it will simply be put into the back of my spellbook like the previous line of pets that I no longer summon.  Allowing the pet to cast Ice Comet is simply not neccessary.  While I'm just as exstatic as any other mage to see my pet cast this spell, as the spell effect is bloody amazing, if it means stepping on a few wizards toes, then by all means forget it.  Any other spell can be put in as substitute to do the same job.  Pissing off an entire community is not exactly something I want to do. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The pet also needs to do a very consistant amount of damage.  If the pet does 130dps for 3 battles and then 20dps for 3 more while it meds, then creates two problems:<br>
<br>
1)  It allows the mage to simply reclaim and resummon and new pet do burst another 130dps.<br>
<br>
2)  It violates the tradition that mage pets are there to do a sustained damage even while the mage is medding.  For instance, the damage of our water pet may fluctuate, but it's pretty much always doing a consistant ~75-80dps every battle if properly positioned.<br>
<br>
So, in order to balance this pet, it must have the following:<br>
<br>
1)  A manapool so large that requiring it to med is unneccessary.<br>
<br>
2a)  Fast casting, low agro, lower damage nukes (~300-500 damage a piece).<br>
<br>
-OR-<br>
<br>
2b)  Concussion for itself, not the mage, which it must analyze the mob's hate list in order to use effectively.  Since a wizard is an actual PC player, they can have a feel for how much agro they are producing and concussion accordingly.  Any decent wizard I know won't be firing off Ice Comet at the start of a fight just as I won't be firing off Firebolt of Tallon at the beginning of one.  The pet neither has this skillful intuition, nor can it afford to make that sort of mistake, as mages are often simply told to kill their pets.<br>
<br>
3)  They need to drop the ice line from the pet.  While the pet is a wizard, and wizards cast ice nukes, the only two forms of ice damage a mage currently has is the water pet's natural 140dd and the procs off Blade of Kedge.  That is the limitation of the mage, as it always has been, and in my opinion always should be.  <br>
<br>
4)  The fire pet needs to have a high innate resistant to fire, as all other pets to do their respective elements.  Air pets are highly resistant to ice.  For instance, Ward of Xegony will not take damage from Gozzrem's 500dd in WToV (Yet is still dispelled?!?).  Water pets are highly resistant to poison and, for instance, will always resist the poison drake's DoT in HoT.  Earth pets are highly resistant to disease and will 99.9% of the time resist ALL shrieker slows, stuns, and fungi form from the mushrooms in FG.  The epic pet has a bit more magic resistance than the others.  If I recall, and correct me if I'm wrong, that the fire pet lost it's fire immunity when it changed from warrior to wizard post 50.  However, since the fire pet is NOT a pet that I currently use at all, I honestly don't have the experience with him.  <br>
<br>
Overall, I'm very happy that SoE is at least addressing this pet.  It has been useless since the beginning of Kunark and has remained ever since.  However, I don't think the fire pet in its current test form is the way it should be.  The current form steps on too many toes and allows for mages to exploit in some way to degree the pet's potential bursting power.  This is not balanced and as a 63 Arch Mage, I will not stand for this.<br>
